e-model-slug="gpt-5-3" class="min-h-8 text-message relative flex w-full flex-col items-end gap-2 text-start break-words whitespace-normal [.text-message+&amp;]:mt-1"><div class="flex w-full flex-col gap-1 empty:hidden first:pt-[1px]"><div class="markdown prose dark:prose-invert w-full wrap-break-word light markdown-new-styling"><p data-start="0" data-end="403">Given your background in <strong data-start="25" data-end="114">precision medicine, oncology data abstraction, cancer genomics, and clinical research</strong>, you actually already have a <strong data-start="144" data-end="170">very strong foundation</strong> for moving into <strong data-start="187" data-end="223">biostatistics with oncology data</strong>. The key now is to <strong data-start="243" data-end="319">translate that domain knowledge into statistical and analytic experience</strong> that employers or research groups can see. Here are some realistic ways to do that.</p>
<hr data-start="405" data-end="408">
<h2 data-start="410" data-end="468">1. Work With Public Oncology Datasets (Best First Step)</h2>
<p data-start="469" data-end="578">You can gain <strong data-start="482" data-end="507">real-world experience</strong> by analyzing publicly available cancer datasets and building projects.</p>
<p data-start="580" data-end="605">Some of the best sources:</p>
<ul data-start="607" data-end="1031">
<li data-start="607" data-end="779">
<p data-start="609" data-end="779"><strong data-start="609" data-end="690"><span class="hover:entity-accent entity-underline inline cursor-pointer align-baseline"><span class="whitespace-normal">National Cancer Institute</span></span> – <span class="hover:entity-accent entity-underline inline cursor-pointer align-baseline"><span class="whitespace-normal">SEER Program</span></span></strong><br data-start="690" data-end="693">
Population-based cancer registry data used widely in epidemiology and biostatistics.</p>
</li>
<li data-start="781" data-end="891">
<p data-start="783" data-end="891"><strong data-start="783" data-end="831"><span class="hover:entity-accent entity-underline inline cursor-pointer align-baseline"><span class="whitespace-normal">The Cancer Genome Atlas</span></span> (TCGA)</strong><br data-start="831" data-end="834">
Genomic, clinical, and molecular data for many cancers.</p>
</li>
<li data-start="893" data-end="1031">
<p data-start="895" data-end="1031"><strong data-start="895" data-end="982"><span class="hover:entity-accent entity-underline inline cursor-pointer align-baseline"><span class="whitespace-normal">National Center for Biotechnology Information</span></span> – <span class="hover:entity-accent entity-underline inline cursor-pointer align-baseline"><span class="whitespace-normal">Gene Expression Omnibus</span></span> (GEO)</strong><br data-start="982" data-end="985">
Gene expression and transcriptomic datasets.</p>
</li>
</ul>
<h3 data-start="1033" data-end="1063">Example portfolio projects</h3>
<ul data-start="1064" data-end="1298">
<li data-start="1064" data-end="1147">
<p data-start="1066" data-end="1147">Survival analysis of lung cancer using <strong data-start="1105" data-end="1147">Kaplan–Meier curves and Cox regression</strong></p>
</li>
<li data-start="1148" data-end="1188">
<p data-start="1150" data-end="1188">Biomarker vs survival outcome modeling</p>
</li>
<li data-start="1189" data-end="1249">
<p data-start="1191" data-end="1249">Treatment outcome comparison by stage or molecular subtype</p>
</li>
<li data-start="1250" data-end="1298">
<p data-start="1252" data-end="1298">Logistic regression predicting metastasis risk</p>
</li>
</ul>
<p data-start="1300" data-end="1321">Tools typically used:</p>
<ul data-start="1322" data-end="1465">
<li data-start="1322" data-end="1365">
<p data-start="1324" data-end="1365"><strong data-start="1324" data-end="1365"><span class="hover:entity-accent entity-underline inline cursor-pointer align-baseline"><span class="whitespace-normal">R (programming language)</span></span></strong></p>
</li>
<li data-start="1366" data-end="1409">
<p data-start="1368" data-end="1409"><strong data-start="1368" data-end="1409"><span class="hover:entity-accent entity-underline inline cursor-pointer align-baseline"><span class="whitespace-normal">RStudio</span></span></strong></p>
</li>
<li data-start="1410" data-end="1465">
<p data-start="1412" data-end="1465">packages: <code data-start="1422" data-end="1432">survival</code>, <code data-start="1434" data-end="1445">tidyverse</code>, <code data-start="1447" data-end="1456">ggplot2</code>, <code data-start="1458" data-end="1465">caret</code></p>
</li>
</ul>
<hr data-start="1467" data-end="1470">
<h2 data-start="1472" data-end="1542">2. Turn Your Oncology Registry Experience Into Statistical Projects</h2>
<p data-start="1543" data-end="1676">Since you already work with <strong data-start="1571" data-end="1605">tumor registry / oncology data</strong>, you can build statistical analyses from <strong data-start="1647" data-end="1675">registry-style variables</strong>.</p>
<p data-start="1678" data-end="1695">Example analyses:</p>
<ul data-start="1697" data-end="1851">
<li data-start="1697" data-end="1734">
<p data-start="1699" data-end="1734">Stage distribution trends over time</p>
</li>
<li data-start="1735" data-end="1771">
<p data-start="1737" data-end="1771">Survival by <strong data-start="1749" data-end="1771">treatment modality</strong></p>
</li>
<li data-start="1772" data-end="1809">
<p data-start="1774" data-end="1809">Demographic disparities in outcomes</p>
</li>
<li data-start="1810" data-end="1851">
<p data-start="1812" data-end="1851">Predictors of <strong data-start="1826" data-end="1851">lymph node metastasis</strong></p>
</li>
</ul>
<p data-start="1853" data-end="1873">Methods to practice:</p>
<ul data-start="1875" data-end="2052">
<li data-start="1875" data-end="1907">
<p data-start="1877" data-end="1907">Kaplan–Meier survival curves</p>
</li>
<li data-start="1908" data-end="1943">
<p data-start="1910" data-end="1943">Cox proportional hazards models</p>
</li>
<li data-start="1944" data-end="1967">
<p data-start="1946" data-end="1967">Logistic regression</p>
</li>
<li data-start="1968" data-end="1991">
<p data-start="1970" data-end="1991">Multiple regression</p>
</li>
<li data-start="1992" data-end="2052">
<p data-start="1994" data-end="2052">Interaction effects (which you’ve already been doing in R)</p>
</li>
</ul>
<p data-start="2054" data-end="2155">This is extremely valuable because <strong data-start="2089" data-end="2154">biostatisticians with real oncology data familiarity are rare</strong>.</p>
<hr data-start="2157" data-end="2160">
<h2 data-start="2162" data-end="2205">3. Collaborate With Academic Researchers</h2>
<p data-start="2206" data-end="2219">Reach out to:</p>
<ul data-start="2221" data-end="2309">
<li data-start="2221" data-end="2241">
<p data-start="2223" data-end="2241">oncology fellows</p>
</li>
<li data-start="2242" data-end="2261">
<p data-start="2244" data-end="2261">epidemiologists</p>
</li>
<li data-start="2262" data-end="2287">
<p data-start="2264" data-end="2287">public health faculty</p>
</li>
<li data-start="2288" data-end="2309">
<p data-start="2290" data-end="2309">cancer registries</p>
</li>
</ul>
<p data-start="2311" data-end="2327">Offer help with:</p>
<ul data-start="2329" data-end="2399">
<li data-start="2329" data-end="2351">
<p data-start="2331" data-end="2351">statistical analysis</p>
</li>
<li data-start="2352" data-end="2363">
<p data-start="2354" data-end="2363">R scripts</p>
</li>
<li data-start="2364" data-end="2383">
<p data-start="2366" data-end="2383">survival modeling</p>
</li>
<li data-start="2384" data-end="2399">
<p data-start="2386" data-end="2399">visualization</p>
</li>
</ul>
<p data-start="2401" data-end="2494">Many research groups <strong data-start="2422" data-end="2493">need someone who understands both oncology variables AND statistics</strong>.</p>
<p data-start="2496" data-end="2512">Places to check:</p>
<ul data-start="2513" data-end="2625">
<li data-start="2513" data-end="2539">
<p data-start="2515" data-end="2539">university research labs</p>
</li>
<li data-start="2540" data-end="2556">
<p data-start="2542" data-end="2556">cancer centers</p>
</li>
<li data-start="2557" data-end="2591">
<p data-start="2559" data-end="2591">tumor registry research projects</p>
</li>
<li data-start="2592" data-end="2625">
<p data-start="2594" data-end="2625">graduate student collaborations</p>
</li>
</ul>
<hr data-start="2627" data-end="2630">
<h2 data-start="2632" data-end="2694">4. Contribute to Clinical Research or Retrospective Studies</h2>
<p data-start="2695" data-end="2734">Many cancer studies require someone to:</p>
<ul data-start="2736" data-end="2807">
<li data-start="2736" data-end="2752">
<p data-start="2738" data-end="2752">clean datasets</p>
</li>
<li data-start="2753" data-end="2783">
<p data-start="2755" data-end="2783">perform statistical analysis</p>
</li>
<li data-start="2784" data-end="2807">
<p data-start="2786" data-end="2807">generate plots/tables</p>
</li>
</ul>
<p data-start="2809" data-end="2826">Typical workflow:</p>
<ol data-start="2828" data-end="2975">
<li data-start="2828" data-end="2865">
<p data-start="2831" data-end="2865">Extract data from registry / EMR</p>
</li>
<li data-start="2866" data-end="2904">
<p data-start="2869" data-end="2904">Clean and structure data in <strong data-start="2897" data-end="2902">R</strong></p>
</li>
<li data-start="2905" data-end="2935">
<p data-start="2908" data-end="2935">Perform statistical tests</p>
</li>
<li data-start="2936" data-end="2975">
<p data-start="2939" data-end="2975">Generate tables and survival plots</p>
</li>
</ol>
<p data-start="2977" data-end="3058">You could easily help on <strong data-start="3002" data-end="3036">retrospective oncology studies</strong>, which are common in:</p>
<ul data-start="3060" data-end="3122">
<li data-start="3060" data-end="3080">
<p data-start="3062" data-end="3080">radiation oncology</p>
</li>
<li data-start="3081" data-end="3100">
<p data-start="3083" data-end="3100">surgical oncology</p>
</li>
<li data-start="3101" data-end="3122">
<p data-start="3103" data-end="3122">hematology/oncology</p>
</li>
</ul>
<hr data-start="3124" data-end="3127">
<h2 data-start="3129" data-end="3172">5. Build a Small Biostatistics Portfolio</h2>
<p data-start="3173" data-end="3214">Create <strong data-start="3180" data-end="3196">3–5 projects</strong> and publish them.</p>
<p data-start="3216" data-end="3237">You can host them on:</p>
<ul data-start="3239" data-end="3326">
<li data-start="3239" data-end="3282">
<p data-start="3241" data-end="3282"><strong data-start="3241" data-end="3282"><span class="hover:entity-accent entity-underline inline cursor-pointer align-baseline"><span class="whitespace-normal">GitHub</span></span></strong></p>
</li>
<li data-start="3283" data-end="3326">
<p data-start="3285" data-end="3326"><strong data-start="3285" data-end="3326"><span class="hover:entity-accent entity-underline inline cursor-pointer align-baseline"><span class="whitespace-normal">Kaggle</span></span></strong></p>
</li>
</ul>
<p data-start="3328" data-end="3356">Example portfolio structure:</p>
<pre class="overflow-visible! px-0!" data-start="3358" data-end="3671"><div class="relative w-full my-4"><div class=""><div class="relative"><div class="h-full min-h-0 min-w-0"><div class="h-full min-h-0 min-w-0" style="width: 100%; transform: none;"><div class="border border-token-border-light border-radius-3xl corner-superellipse/1.1 rounded-3xl"><div class="h-full w-full border-radius-3xl bg-token-bg-elevated-secondary corner-superellipse/1.1 overflow-clip rounded-3xl lxnfua_clipPathFallback"><div class="pointer-events-none absolute end-1.5 top-1 z-2 md:end-2 md:top-1"><button class="flex gap-1 items-center select-none pointer-events-auto py-2 text-sm font-medium hover:bg-black/5 dark:hover:bg-white/10 size-9 rounded-full px-2" aria-label="Copy" data-state="closed"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="20" height="20" aria-hidden="true" class="icon-md"><use href="/cdn/assets/sprites-core-eri7ssmm.svg#ce3544" fill="currentColor"></use></svg></button></div><div class="pt-3" style="transform: none;"><div class="relative z-0 flex max-w-full"><div id="code-block-viewer" dir="ltr" class="q9tKkq_viewer cm-editor z-10 light:cm-light dark:cm-light flex h-full w-full flex-col items-stretch ͼ5 ͼj"><div class="cm-scroller"><div class="cm-content q9tKkq_readonly"><span>oncology-biostatistics-portfolio/</span><br><br><span>1_lung_cancer_survival_analysis</span><br><span>   - R script</span><br><span>   - Kaplan-Meier plots</span><br><span>   - Cox regression output</span><br><br><span>2_biomarker_logistic_regression</span><br><span>   - feature analysis</span><br><span>   - ROC curve</span><br><br><span>3_stage_trend_analysis</span><br><span>   - SEER dataset</span><br><span>   - visualization</span><br><br><span>4_gene_expression_modeling</span><br><span>   - TCGA data</span></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div><div class=""><div class="" style="width: 100%; transform: none;"></div></div></div></div></div></pre>
<p data-start="3673" data-end="3736">Employers LOVE seeing <strong data-start="3695" data-end="3735">real statistical work with real data</strong>.</p>
<hr data-start="3738" data-end="3741">
<h2 data-start="3743" data-end="3787">6. Volunteer With Cancer Data Initiatives</h2>
<p data-start="3788" data-end="3831">Some organizations let analysts contribute:</p>
<ul data-start="3833" data-end="3984">
<li data-start="3833" data-end="3876">
<p data-start="3835" data-end="3876"><strong data-start="3835" data-end="3876"><span class="hover:entity-accent entity-underline inline cursor-pointer align-baseline"><span class="whitespace-normal">American Association for Cancer Research</span></span></strong></p>
</li>
<li data-start="3877" data-end="3922">
<p data-start="3879" data-end="3922"><strong data-start="3879" data-end="3922"><span class="hover:entity-accent entity-underline inline cursor-pointer align-baseline"><span class="whitespace-normal">American Society of Clinical Oncology</span></span></strong></p>
</li>
<li data-start="3923" data-end="3984">
<p data-start="3925" data-end="3984">**<span class="hover:entity-accent entity-underline inline cursor-pointer align-baseline"><span class="whitespace-normal">National Cancer Institute</span></span> research programs</p>
</li>
</ul>
<p data-start="3986" data-end="4006">They sometimes have:</p>
<ul data-start="4007" data-end="4077">
<li data-start="4007" data-end="4029">
<p data-start="4009" data-end="4029">open data challenges</p>
</li>
<li data-start="4030" data-end="4054">
<p data-start="4032" data-end="4054">collaborative projects</p>
</li>
<li data-start="4055" data-end="4077">
<p data-start="4057" data-end="4077">research fellowships</p>
</li>
</ul>
<hr data-start="4079" data-end="4082">
<h2 data-start="4084" data-end="4130">7. Learn Key Oncology Biostatistics Methods</h2>
<p data-start="4131" data-end="4191">These are the <strong data-start="4145" data-end="4190">most important methods in cancer research</strong>:</p>
<p data-start="4193" data-end="4206">Core methods:</p>
<ul data-start="4207" data-end="4334">
<li data-start="4207" data-end="4237">
<p data-start="4209" data-end="4237">Kaplan–Meier survival curves</p>
</li>
<li data-start="4238" data-end="4275">
<p data-start="4240" data-end="4275">Cox proportional hazards regression</p>
</li>
<li data-start="4276" data-end="4297">
<p data-start="4278" data-end="4297">Logistic regression</p>
</li>
<li data-start="4298" data-end="4312">
<p data-start="4300" data-end="4312">Mixed models</p>
</li>
<li data-start="4313" data-end="4334">
<p data-start="4315" data-end="4334">Multiple regression</p>
</li>
</ul>
<p data-start="4336" data-end="4370">Advanced methods (optional later):</p>
<ul data-start="4371" data-end="4477">
<li data-start="4371" data-end="4395">
<p data-start="4373" data-end="4395">competing risks models</p>
</li>
<li data-start="4396" data-end="4423">
<p data-start="4398" data-end="4423">time-dependent covariates</p>
</li>
<li data-start="4424" data-end="4442">
<p data-start="4426" data-end="4442">genomic modeling</p>
</li>
<li data-start="4443" data-end="4477">
<p data-start="4445" data-end="4477">machine learning survival models</p>
</li>
</ul>
<hr data-start="4479" data-end="4482">
<p data-start="4484" data-end="4640">💡 <strong data-start="4487" data-end="4522">The biggest advantage you have:</strong><br data-start="4522" data-end="4525">
Most statisticians <strong data-start="4544" data-end="4588">don’t understand oncology data variables</strong> (TNM staging, biomarkers, treatments, pathology).</p>
<p data-start="4642" data-end="4796">Because you <strong data-start="4654" data-end="4697">already understand the clinical meaning</strong>, learning the statistical modeling will make you <strong data-start="4747" data-end="4795">very valuable in precision medicine research</strong>.</p>
<hr data-start="4798" data-end="4801">
<p data-start="4803" data-end="4838">✅ If you want, I can also show you:</p>
<p data-start="4840" data-end="5096" data-is-last-node="" data-is-only-node="">1️⃣ <strong data-start="4844" data-end="4920">A step-by-step plan to become an oncology biostatistician in 6–12 months</strong><br data-start="4920" data-end="4923">
2️⃣ <strong data-start="4927" data-end="4993">3 oncology biostatistics projects you can start this week in R</strong><br data-start="4993" data-end="4996">
