v id="code-block-viewer" dir="ltr" class="q9tKkq_viewer cm-editor z-10 light:cm-light dark:cm-light flex h-full w-full flex-col items-stretch ͼ5 ͼj"><div class="cm-scroller"><div class="cm-content q9tKkq_readonly"><span># Survival Analysis by Stage at Diagnosis in Lung Cancer</span><br><br><span>## Overview</span><br><span>This project examines whether stage at diagnosis affects overall survival in patients with lung cancer.</span><br><br><span>## Clinical Question</span><br><span>Does stage at diagnosis affect overall survival in patients with lung cancer?</span><br><br><span>## Objective</span><br><span>To compare survival across stage groups using Kaplan–Meier survival curves and a log-rank test, and to estimate the association between stage at diagnosis and hazard of death using a Cox proportional hazards model adjusted for age and sex.</span><br><br><span>## Variables</span><br><span>- survival_months: time from diagnosis to death or last follow-up</span><br><span>- status: event indicator (1 = death, 0 = censored)</span><br><span>- stage: stage at diagnosis (I, II, III, IV)</span><br><span>- age: age at diagnosis</span><br><span>- sex: patient sex</span><br><br><span>## Methods</span><br><span>- Kaplan–Meier survival curves</span><br><span>- Log-rank test</span><br><span>- Cox proportional hazards regression</span><br><br><span>## Files</span><br><span>- `data/lung_cancer_survival.csv`</span><br><span>- `scripts/survival_analysis.R`</span><br><span>- `output/figures/km_plot.png`</span><br><span>- `output/tables/cox_results.csv`</span><br><br><span>## Interpretation</span><br><span>This project demonstrates the use of standard oncology biostatistics methods to evaluate the relationship between stage at diagnosis and overall survival.</span></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div><div class=""><div class="" style="width: 100%; transform: none;"></div></div></div></div></div></pre>
<hr data-start="7226" data-end="7229">
<h1 data-start="7231" data-end="7292">How to make this look especially strong for your background</h1>
<p data-start="7294" data-end="7383">Because you already know oncology, add a short clinical interpretation section like this:</p>
<blockquote data-start="7385" data-end="7751">
<p data-start="7387" data-end="7751">Stage at diagnosis is one of the 
most important prognostic factors in lung cancer. Earlier-stage disease 
is generally associated with more treatment options and improved 
survival, whereas advanced-stage disease often reflects metastatic 
spread and poorer outcomes. This analysis evaluates whether the expected
 survival gradient by stage is observed in the dataset.</p>
</blockquote>
<p data-start="7753" data-end="7876">That makes the project feel much more like <strong data-start="7796" data-end="7831">real oncology outcomes research</strong> and less like a generic stats homework file.</p>
